        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Montreal</placeName>
                <date>8th May 5625</date>.</p>
            <p>
                <addressee>Rev. Isaac Leeser</addressee>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Dear Sir-</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">I send you herewith<lb/> fifty Dollars which will balance the<lb/>
                amount of my indebtedness to you for<lb/> Books &amp; printing to date. The
                following<lb/> is a statement as per your favors of<lb/>
                <date>September</date> last &amp;c</p>
            <table cols="3" rows="12">
                <row>
                    <cell>“10 Sets will cost you</cell>
                    <cell>17.</cell>
                    <cell>$170</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell> less 20 per cent</cell>
                    <cell/>
                    <cell>
                        <hi rend="underline"> 34</hi>
                    </cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell/>
                    <cell/>
                    <cell>136</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell> add binding 70 vols</cell>
                    <cell>60</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <hi rend="underline"> 42</hi>
                    </cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell> 6 daily</cell>
                    <cell>3.25—19.50</cell>
                    <cell>178</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell> less 20 per cent</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <hi rend="underline">3.80</hi>
                    </cell>
                    <cell>
                        <hi rend="underline">15.70</hi>
                    </cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell/>
                    <cell> 15.70</cell>
                    <cell>193.70</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Printing Sermon &amp; Biography</cell>
                    <cell/>
                    <cell>
                        <hi rend="underline"> 31.00</hi>
                    </cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell/>
                    <cell/>
                    <cell>224 70</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>cr.</cell>
                    <cell/>
                    <cell/>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><date>Sep '54</date> By draft</cell>
                    <cell> 175</cell>
                    <cell/>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><date>May 55</date> “ Bills</cell>
                    <cell>50</cell>
                    <cell>225.</cell>
                </row>
            </table>
            <p>leaving 30 cents to my credit; though</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>there will be due you $9 for <persName>Mrs<lb/> Naapers</persName> subscription to
                the Occident.<lb/>—I have been hunting everywhere<lb/> to <hi rend="underline"
                    >elucidate</hi> this matter, but though<lb/> I have entries of monies paid on
                your<lb/> account in <date>1860</date> I cannot find that<lb/> I paid <persName>Mr
                    Joseph</persName> that identical amount.<lb/> But as <persName>Mrs N.</persName>
                paid, &amp; you did not receive<lb/> the amount I am the defaultee, and<lb/> will
                send it you another time, as I<lb/> could only readily obtain today $50<lb/> in your
                currency—now pretty near<lb/> our own in value. While I write<lb/> it occurs to me
                you could pay yourself<lb/> &amp; accommodate me, if you would<lb/> let me draw
                through you on<lb/> the esteemed editor of the <placeName>N. Y.</placeName>
                Jewish<lb/> Record who owes me a <add>?</add><lb/> amount <add>עששת ימי
                בראשית</add>. Let me know,<lb/> please, if you would like to do this<lb/> and I will
                send you the order.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">You would oblige me when<lb/> you send the Occidents to let me
                have</p>
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p>at the same time the subjoined nos of the<lb/>
                <sic>occident</sic> which I require to complete<lb/> *my pyle—Except 3, they are all
                of<lb/> the weekly series and failed to reach<lb/> me through irregularity of the
                Post Office</p>
            <list type="simple">
                <head/>
                <item>Vol 14 nos 1,2.</item>
                <item rend="indent(1)"> 15 no 5.</item>
                <item rend="indent(1)"> 17 nos 23, 25, 26, 28, 31, 43.</item>
                <item rend="indent(1)"> 18 nos 6, 12, 40, 41, 47, 49, 51</item>
            </list>
            <p>You can send them by mail—the weeklies<lb/> can go in one wrapper.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">In a recent letter you ask<lb/> whether something can't be done
                with<lb/> the <persName>Benjamins</persName>. I before wrote you<lb/> enclose your
                account and I will<lb/> do what I can with <persName>Wm Benjamin</persName><lb/>
                here. You also are surprised<lb/> that your subscribers here are, so few, but
                    <add>בעה"ר</add> Jews don't<lb/> increase in <placeName>Canada</placeName>. If
                you have<lb/> no field here, be comforted with<lb/> the reflection that neither have
                I</p>
            <pb n="4"/>
            <p>nor any one else. It is because I have<lb/> as good a position as a Jew could<lb/>
                obtain among <add>?</add>, and that my<lb/> position at College has greatly
                improved<lb/> that I am satisfied with the extent<lb/> of my Jewish field. I presume<lb/>
                <persName>Mr Joseph</persName> paid you for his set of<lb/> prayers in sheets, which
                I duly handed<lb/> him. I am greatly obliged to you<lb/> for the portrait which I
                have appropriated<lb/> to myself—the other one we have I don't<lb/> think so good. I
                send you some<lb/> verses written by an esteemed &amp; talented<lb/> friend
                    <persName>Miss Sarah Livia</persName> of <placeName>London</placeName> on
                the<lb/> death of my brother <persName>Isaac</persName>
                <add>?</add> which from<lb/> their religious fervor you may think<lb/> worthy of
                publishing in the Occident.<lb/>
                <persName>Miss Livia</persName> who is not sufficiently known<lb/> to our people has
                    <add>?</add> for some years<lb/> some excellent pieces in prose as well as<lb/>
                poetry to various <placeName>London</placeName> magazines and<lb/> no doubt, had not
                her natural retiringness<lb/> been in the way, she would worthily have<lb/> filled
                the place left vacant by <persName>Grace Aguilar</persName>. I send<lb/> the lines
                rather to show that the true <add>?</add> is<lb/> among</p>
            <p rend="Letter cuts off here."/>
        </body>
